`this range `-128 to 127 range values cache பண்ணும்`means if 128 is out of cache right?`

ஆமாம் 👍 — **defaultஆ** `Integer` cache range:

👉 **-128 முதல் 127 வரை (inclusive)**
👉 அதனால் **128 → cacheக்கு வெளியே** ❌

---

# 🔹 Simple demo

```java
Integer a = 127;
Integer b = 127;
System.out.println(a == b);  // true (cached)

Integer x = 128;
Integer y = 128;
System.out.println(x == y);  // false (not cached)
```

---

# 🔹 Why 128 not cached?

👉 JVM default cache:

```text
-128  ...  127   ✔️ cached
128, 129 ...     ❌ not cached
```

👉 அதனால்:

* 127 → same object reuse ✔️
* 128 → new objects create ❌

---

# 🔴 BUT important twist 🔥

👉 இந்த range **change பண்ண முடியும்** 😎

### JVM option:

```bash
-XX:AutoBoxCacheMax=200
```

👉 இதை set பண்ணினா:

```text
-128 to 200 → cached
```

👉 அப்போ:

```java
Integer x = 128;
Integer y = 128;
System.out.println(x == y);  // true 😲
```

---

# 🔹 Important takeaway

👉 ✔️ Default:

➡️ **-128 to 127**

👉 ✔️ Customizable (advanced use)

---

# 🔹 One more important note 🔥

👉 இது apply ஆகும்:

* Integer ✔️
* Short ✔️
* Byte ✔️
* Long ✔️
* Character (0–127) ✔️

👉 Float, Double ❌ cache இல்லை

---

# 🔥 Final clarity

👉 ✔️ 128 → default cacheக்கு வெளியே
👉 ✔️ அதனால் new object create ஆகும்

